<Layout title="How Brisbane City Council Rates Are Calculated: What Sellers Need to Know | Daniel Gierach Property" description="Council rates appear on every settlement adjustment statement. Here is how Brisbane City Council calculates rates, why investment properties pay more, and what sellers should tell buyers." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How are Brisbane City Council rates calculated?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Brisbane City Council rates are calculated using the State Government's land valuation (site value) for your property, multiplied by a rate-in-the-dollar set by BCC. The rate-in-the-dollar varies by property category: owner-occupier residential properties pay a lower rate than non-owner-occupier (investment) properties. Additional levies including the Environment Levy, Cycling Levy, and Tariff 12 water and sewerage charges are added on top."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why do investment properties pay higher council rates in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Brisbane City Council uses a differential rating system. Non-owner-occupier residential properties, which includes investment properties and rentals, attract a higher rate-in-the-dollar than owner-occupier properties. This is a deliberate policy choice by BCC and the difference can be significant, so buyers purchasing as investors should always check the current rates notice rather than assuming the seller's rate applies."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do council rates affect the settlement of a Brisbane property sale?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Council rates are adjusted between buyer and seller at settlement. If the seller has paid rates in advance beyond the settlement date, the buyer reimburses the unused portion. If rates are in arrears, the seller pays their share. Having a recent rates notice available for buyers reduces questions during the campaign and speeds up the conveyancing process."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
